Based on your current script, the answer is yes, it will support graphs and tables, and yes, you can download it—but there are two specific things you need to do to make it work correctly.
1. Will it show Graphs and Tables?
The JMeter HTML dashboard (-e -o /report/html) is very rich. It includes:
Tables: Statistics table, Errors table, and Top 5 Errors by Sampler.
Graphs: Response times over time, Throughput (Hits/sec), Latencies, and Active Threads.
The Catch: Jenkins has a strict Content Security Policy (CSP). By default, it blocks the JavaScript and CSS used by the JMeter report. If you open the report and it looks like a broken text page with no graphs, you need to run this command in the Jenkins Script Console (Manage Jenkins > Nodes > Built-in Node > Script Console):


System.setProperty("hudson.model.DirectoryBrowserSupport.csp", "default-src 'self' 'unsafe-inline' 'unsafe-eval'; img-src 'self' data:;")

Note: This reset is temporary and clears on a Jenkins restart. For a permanent fix, add it to your Jenkins startup flags.

2. Can you download it?
The publishHTML step makes the report viewable in the browser, but it's not a single "downloadable" file because it's a folder full of HTML, JS, and CSS files.
To make it easily downloadable as a single package, you should add the archiveArtifacts step to your post block.
Updated Post Block

post {
  always {
    // 1. Makes it viewable in Jenkins sidebar
    publishHTML(target: [
      reportDir: 'performance-report/html',
      reportFiles: 'index.html',
      reportName: 'Performance Test Report',
      keepAll: true,
      alwaysLinkToLastBuild: true,
      allowMissing: false
    ])

    // 2. Makes the entire folder & results.csv downloadable as a ZIP
    archiveArtifacts artifacts: 'performance-report/**', fingerprint: true
  }
}



